         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility"> ¶ [Acacia Melanoxylon, the celebrated Black-Wood of Australia, used in the manufacture of railway coaches, interior finish, etc. These seeds were ordered from and selected by Baron Von Mueller, of Me...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">72.00.00b</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From […]</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Letter not found. The text given here is from 'The <name key="Eucalyptus">Eucalyptus</name>', <seg style="font-style: italic; ">New Orleans bulletin</seg>, 28 November 1875, p. 3. The article begins</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0.6681in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>A distinguished firm of seedsmen and florists of San Francisco recently received from Udolpho Wolfe &amp; Co, of New York, an order for seeds of sundry varieties of the <name key="Eucalyptus">Eucalyptus</name> or Blue Gum Tree, other wise known as the Tasmanian Fever Tree. When filling the order, the senior member of the firm wrote an interesting letter, noting facts relative to the <name key="Eucalyptus">Eucalyptus</name>, which may be interesting to many of the readers of the <seg style="font-variant: small-caps; ">Bulletin</seg>.' </p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The article contains a list of <name key="Eucalyptus">Eucalyptus</name> species together with 'Casuerina (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">sic</seg>) suberosa' and the <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Acacia melanoxylon</seg> comment extracted here.</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The San Francisco firm that ordered seed from M and supplied Wolfe &amp; Co has not been identified. Their letter to M is tentatively dated to no later than 1872, on the basis of the quoted comment in the article that 'I have [<seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Eucalyptus">Eucalyptus</name>
                     </seg>] trees less than three years from the seed, now twenty-five to thirty feet high and twenty to thirty inches in circumference', and the assumption that these were grown from early seeds obtained from M.</p>
               </note>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>[<name key="Acacia%20Melanoxylon">Acacia Melanoxylon</name>, the celebrated Black-Wood of Australia, used in the manufacture of railway coaches, interior finish, etc. These seeds were ordered from and selected by Baron Von Mueller, of Melbourne Botanical Gardens, from the healthiest and most symmetrical trees which could be found. </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">…</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have been raising the [<name key="Eucalyptus">Eucalyptus</name>] trees by the 100,000 and have tried in all ways all seeds. The most complete success I have had, has been from seed selected for me by Baron von Mueller, at Melbourne, on direct order.]</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Acacia%20Melanoxylon">Acacia Melanoxylon</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Eucalyptus">Eucalyptus</name>
            </p>
